The '''ostrich instruction''' is a [[jury instruction]] that the requirement of [[knowledge]] to establish a guilty mind ([[mens rea]]), is satisfied by deliberate ignorance - deliberate avoidance of knowledge.<ref name=OIDI>Ostrich Instruction: Deliberate Ignorance as a Criminal Mens Rea, Journal of Criminal Law and Criminology, Volume 81  Issue 2, Summer 1990 Pages 191-234; I P Robbins, [https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/publications/abstract.aspx?ID=125924]</ref> It arose from the case of ''[[United States v. Jewell]]''.<ref name=CL>''Criminal Law - Cases and Materials'', 7th ed. 2012, [[Wolters Kluwer Law & Business]]; [[John Kaplan (law professor)|John Kaplan]], [[Robert Weisberg]], [[Guyora Binder]], {{ISBN|978-1-4548-0698-1}}, [https://law.stanford.edu/publications/criminal-law-cases-and-materials-7th-edition/]</ref>{{rp|762}}

