The '''Valle Trita''' was a remote area lying beneath the highest peak in the [[Apennine Mountains|Central Apennines]]. It was mainly [[forest]] and [[pasture]]land, classified as a ''gualdus'' during the [[Lombards|Lombard period]].{{sfn|Wickham|2005|pp=583–85}} It is famous for the long dispute between its inhabitants and the monastery of [[San Vincenzo al Volturno]] in the early [[Middle Ages]].

The Valle Trita belonged to the [[royal fisc]] until about 758, when King [[Desiderius]] granted it to San Vincenzo about 100 kilometres away. The monastery began collecting as rents the dues (or taxes) formerly owed to the crown.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|pp=583–85}} The monks built up an estate in the valley and claimed that the peasants were [[slaves]] who did not own the land but owed service to the monastery for their right to it.{{sfn|Wickham|1981|pp=110–11}} The peasants claimed that they were free, and could produce precepts (''precepta'') of the [[Dukes of Spoleto]], the highest local Lombard official, to that effect.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|pp=583–85}}

In 779, after the [[Carolingian Empire|Carolingians]] had replaced the Lombards, the monastery brought the peasants to court to enforce their obedience. It won, but the peasants did not accept the verdict.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|pp=583–85}} In 787, Abbot Paul brought a petition to King [[Charlemagne]], who confirmed Desiderius' grant of Trita to the monastery.{{sfn|Balzaretti|1999|p=392|ps=. For the diploma, cf. E. Mühlbacher, ed., ''Diplomata Karolinorum'' I, [[Monumenta Germaniae Historica|MGH]] (Berlin, 1906), [http://www.mgh.de/dmgh/resolving/MGH_DD_Kar._1_S._216 doc. 159], which calls the place ''villam Trite sitam'', a village at the place of Trita.}} The peasants were taken to court again that year and in 822, 823, 824, 854, 872 and 873: a total of eight court cases for which records survive in the [[cartulary]] of the monastery.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|p=583 n. 125. The cartulary is preserved in the house chronicle, the ''[[Chronicon Vulturnense]]''}} The records also indicate a ninth court challenge, for which the proceedings have not survived, took place. San Vincenzo won every trial, but was unable to consistently enforce the rulings in the remote area.{{sfn|Wickham|1981|pp=110–11}} After the 854 ruling it had some success in forcing ''[[corvée]]'' from the peasants, who worked twelve weeks a year for the monastery.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|p=296 and n. 79}} In January 873, when the peasants refused to attend court, the army of the [[Emperor Louis II]], which was in the area, rounded them up and brought them to trial. The cold weather had prevented the peasants from taking to higher ground.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|pp=583–85}}

In 881 San Vincenzo was sacked by [[History of Islam in southern Italy|Muslim raiders]] and lost control over most of its estates for decades. The Valle Trita is not recorded again in the monastic cartulary until 998. [[Chris Wickham]] concludes that in all of Europe only at Trita did peasants successfully resist intrusive lordship for a long period before 900.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|pp=583–85}} Nevertheless, the peasant resistance of Trita may be only the best chronicled of many cases of remote pastoral communities with a history of independence resisting [[feudalisation]] in central Italy.{{sfn|Wickham|2005|p=588}} More rare, but better recorded were the wide-ranging and violent revolts of the lower classes, such as the contemporary Saxon ''[[Stellinga]]'' in 841–42.

